The funnel and vane + funnel traps were compared in Experiment 4 with vane + funnel traps with black painted vanes at Bah Lias Estate (11 ± 25 April 1994; N = 15) in a mixed cocoacoconut planting. Intertrap and interblock distances were 45 m. All traps contained ferrugineol and half coconut husks.
In short date palms, the presence of unsevered leaf axils minimized contact between standard bucket traps and the trunk. Black buckets were more readily obtainable than white buckets in the United Arab Emirates (UAE). Consequently, the standard trap (white upright) was compared with three other trap designs in Experiment 5 (inverted white bucket, upright black bucket and inverted black bucket) (figure 1) in Ras Al Kaimeh, UAE (12 ± 20 June 1993; N = 10). White buckets available in the UAE were very glossy such that weevils could not easily climb into the traps. Thus, surfaces of all white traps were roughened to permit APW to enter the traps. Inverted bucket traps had entry holes near the top and bottom of bucket and all traps contained ferrugineol and date palm tissue soaked in 0.3% a.i. solution of Lannate.

